 fantasy has great potential for informing the way we understand and study all inter-religious and ethnic conflicts.Whether you find yourself agreeing with the arguments in this book or not, you are sure to find it a welcome change from both the existing, mainly conservative, analyses of the Northern Ireland conflict and traditional approaches to conflict resolution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBritishzNorthern IrelandxPsychology. 0aConflict managementzNorthern IrelandxPsychological aspects. 0aIrishzNorthern IrelandxPsychology. 4aSecurity, Conflict & Peace 2018. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / General.2bisacsh  aIrish Republican Army.  aLacanian psychoanalysis.  aNorthern Ireland.  aconflict management.  aconflict resolution.  acontradictions.  ajokes.  aloyalists.  arationalisations.  asocio-ideological fantasy.1 aMillar, Adrian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779225940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847792259423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847792259/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles